# The Impact of Climate Change on Tourism: A Comprehensive Analysis

## Introduction

Tourism is one of the largest and fastest-growing economic sectors globally, contributing significantly to GDP, employment, and international trade. In 2016, the travel and tourism industry accounted for 10.2% of the global GDP and 6.6% of the world’s total annual export, with projections indicating further growth by 2027 ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)). However, tourism is highly climate-sensitive, relying on stable weather patterns and natural environments. Climate change, characterized by rising global temperatures, sea-level rise, increased frequency and intensity of extreme weather events, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss, poses significant challenges to the sustainability and viability of tourism worldwide.

This report provides an in-depth, structured analysis of how climate change affects tourism, drawing on a range of reliable and up-to-date sources. It explores the multifaceted impacts on different tourism segments, including coastal, mountain, forest, safari, and marine tourism, and discusses implications for tourism demand, infrastructure, and the environment. The report also examines mitigation and adaptation strategies within the tourism sector, offering a balanced perspective on challenges and opportunities.

