## 1. Climate Change and Tourism Demand Patterns

Tourism demand is strongly influenced by climate, natural environment, and personal safety. Climate change affects all three, reshaping tourist behaviors and destination preferences.

- **Shift in Tourist Preferences:** Tourists from temperate regions are expected to modify travel plans to exploit new climatic conditions closer to home, potentially reducing visits to traditionally warmer destinations. This shift may increase domestic and regional tourism spending while decreasing international travel to warmer countries ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)).

- **Seasonality Changes:** Climate change may alter the length and timing of tourism seasons. For example, warmer summers in northern coastal areas could lengthen the summer season, while traditional beach destinations like the Mediterranean might experience extended shoulder seasons ([Ali, 2014](https://skift.com/2014/03/31/how-climate-change-is-threatening-coastal-tourism-and-recreation/)).

- **Tourist Adaptability:** Tourists can avoid destinations affected by adverse climate impacts or adjust travel timing to avoid unfavorable conditions, demonstrating higher adaptability compared to fixed tourism infrastructure ([Njoroge, 2015](https://www.academia.edu/)).

