## 2. Impacts on Key Tourism Destinations and Segments

### 2.1 Coastal and Island Tourism

Coastal and island destinations are among the most vulnerable to climate change due to:

- **Sea-Level Rise:** A projected 1-meter sea-level rise by 2100 threatens to inundate airports, ports, and resorts, particularly in the Caribbean, where rebuilding costs could reach US$10–23.3 billion by 2050 ([Ali, 2014](https://skift.com/2014/03/31/how-climate-change-is-threatening-coastal-tourism-and-recreation/)).

- **Coastal Erosion and Infrastructure Damage:** Increased storms and flooding cause erosion and physical damage to tourism infrastructure, reducing beach areas and compromising ecosystem services.

- **Coral Reef Degradation:** Ocean warming and acidification lead to coral bleaching, threatening reef-based tourism, which contributes over US$11.5 billion globally ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)).

- **Adaptive Capacity:** Many coastal destinations, especially in developing and small island nations, have low adaptive capacity, exacerbating vulnerability.

| Impact Factor         | Description                                                                 | Example Regions              |
|----------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------|
| Sea-Level Rise       | Inundation of key infrastructure and loss of beach areas                     | Caribbean, Vietnam (Cua Dai)|
| Coastal Erosion      | Loss of beaches and natural barriers                                         | Martinique, Caribbean       |
| Coral Bleaching      | Loss of coral reefs affecting marine biodiversity and tourism attractiveness | Great Barrier Reef, Indian Ocean |
| Extreme Weather      | Increased storms and flooding damaging infrastructure                        | Caribbean, Southeast Asia   |

### 2.2 Mountain and Winter Tourism

Mountainous regions rely heavily on snow cover and stable winter conditions:

- **Glacier Melting and Snow Decline:** Rising temperatures reduce snow reliability, shortening ski seasons and threatening winter sports tourism ([Christoff, 2017](https://www.travelpulse.com/news/destinations/how-climate-change-is-affecting-tourism.html)).

- **Seasonal Shifts:** Shorter winters and longer summers may create opportunities for diversified activities like hiking, mountain biking, and spas.

- **Adaptation Measures:** Artificial snowmaking, ski slope grooming, insurance improvements, and emergency preparedness can mitigate some impacts but may increase operational costs and environmental pressures ([Njoroge, 2015](https://www.academia.edu/)).

### 2.3 Forest and Biodiversity Tourism

- **Increased Forest Fires:** Climate change is projected to increase forest fires by 12% in the Amazon basin by 2050, threatening biodiversity and tourism activities such as hiking and bird watching ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)).

- **Species Range Shifts:** Changes in habitat suitability may reduce wildlife sightings, negatively impacting ecotourism and safari experiences.

### 2.4 Safari Destinations

- **Extreme Weather Disruptions:** Flooding and storms have already caused temporary closures of key safari routes, such as the 2012 flooding in Kenya’s Maasai Mara, disrupting tourism and local economies ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)).

### 2.5 Ocean and Sea Life Tourism

- **Marine Biodiversity Loss:** Ocean acidification and warming threaten calcium-producing organisms, leading to coral reef bleaching and habitat loss for marine species ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)).

- **Rising Popularity and Pressure:** Diving tourism is growing at 20% annually, four times faster than global tourism, increasing pressure on vulnerable marine ecosystems ([Sawe, 2020](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/how-is-tourism-affected-by-climate-change.html)).

