## 3. Economic and Social Implications

- **Economic Losses:** Extreme weather events such as hurricanes and floods cause significant economic damage to tourism infrastructure and reduce tourist arrivals, as seen in Florida after Hurricane Irma, which resulted in a loss of approximately $2.5 billion in tourism revenue ([UKEssays, 2019](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/tourism/impact-of-climate-change-on-the-tourism-industry.php)).

- **Employment Impact:** Tourism contributes significantly to employment; climate-induced declines in tourism can lead to job losses, especially in regions heavily dependent on the sector.

- **Community Well-being:** Environmental degradation and climate risks can negatively affect residents' health, well-being, and quality of life, potentially leading to social instability ([Garau-Vadell et al., 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2211973617300395)).

---

## 4. Tourism Sector’s Contribution to Climate Change

Tourism itself contributes approximately 5-10% of global greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, primarily from transportation (75%), with aviation accounting for 40% of these emissions ([Christoff, 2017](https://www.travelpulse.com/news/destinations/how-climate-change-is-affecting-tourism.html); [UNWTO, 2008](https://www.unwto.org/climate-change-and-tourism-responding-to-global-challenges)).

| Source of Emissions | Percentage of Tourism Sector Emissions |
|---------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Transportation      | 75%                                   |
| Aviation            | 40% of transportation emissions      |
| Accommodation      | 20%                                   |
| Activities and Others| 5%                                    |

